A plane figure having four angles, and consequently four sides;any figure having four angles.
Prediction; prophecy.It is not a false utterance; it is a true, though an impetuous,vaticination. I. Taylor.
Loaded; freighted; burdened; as, a laden vessel; a laden heart.Ah sinful nation, a people laden with iniquity. Is. i. 4.A ship laden with gold. Shak.
One of the legs of the loose drawers worn by children andwomen; particularly, the lower part of such a garment, coming belowthe knee, often made in a separate piece; -- chiefly in the plural.

Land adjoining a road or highway; the part of a road or highwaythat borders the traveled part. Also used ajectively.
Capable of being inferred or deduced from premises. [Writtenalso inferrible.] H. Spencer.A sufficient argument . . . is inferable from these premises. Burke.
